{"cursor":"14141","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n{{Infobox writer \n| name = Lucius Junius Moderatus Columella image = Columella.JPG image_size =\n| 250 alt = caption = Statue of Columella, holding a sickle and an ox-yoke, in\n| the Plaza de las Flores, CÃ¡diz pseudonym = birth_name = birth_date = 4 A.D.\n| birth_place = Gades death_date = c. 70 A.D. death_place = resting_place =\n| occupation = language = nationality = ethnicity = citizenship = Roman\n| notableworks = De re rustica influences = influenced =\n}}\n\n'Lucius Junius Moderatus Columella' (Gades, Hispania Baetica, AD 4 â ca. AD 70)\nis the most important writer on agriculture of the Roman empire. Little is known\nof his life. He was probably born in Gades (modern Cadiz), possibly of Roman\nparents. After a career in the army (he was tribune in Syria in 35), he took up\nfarming. His De Re Rustica in twelve volumes has been completely preserved and\nforms an important source on Roman agriculture, together with the works of Cato\nthe Elder and Varro, both of which he occasionally cites. A smaller book on\ntrees, De Arboribus, is usually attributed to him.\n\nColumella used many sources no longer extant, to which he is one of the few\nreferences; these include Aulus Cornelius Celsus, the Carthaginian writer Mago,\nTremellius Scrofa, and many Greek sources. His uncle Marcus Columella, \"a clever\nman and an exceptional farmer\" (VII.2.30), had conducted experiments in sheep\nbreeding, crossing colourful wild rams, introduced from Africa for gladiatorial\ngames, with domestic sheep, and may have influenced his nephew's\ninterests. Columella owned farms in Italy; he refers specifically to estates at\nArdea, Carseoli, and Alba, and speaks repeatedly of his own\npractical experience in agriculture.\n\nPreviously known only in fragments, the complete works of Columella were among\nthose discovered in monastery libraries in Switzerland and France by Poggio\nBracciolini and his assistant Bartolomeo di Montepulciano during the Council of\nConstance, between 1414 and 1418.\n\nIn 1794 the Spanish botanists Jose Antonio PavÃ³n y Jimenez and HipÃ³lito Ruiz\nLÃ³pez named a genus of Peruvian asterid Columellia in his honour.\n","linknr":204,"url":"Lucius_Columella","recorded":1374547445,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Columella&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Columella&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Columella","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","/w/index.php?title=Lucius_Columella&redirect=no","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/Columella_(disambiguation)","/wiki/File:Columella.JPG","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/ee/Columella.JPG/250px-Columella.JPG","/wiki/Sickle","/wiki/Yoke","/wiki/C%C3%A1diz","/wiki/Gades","/wiki/Gades","/wiki/Hispania_Baetica","/wiki/Roman_empire","/wiki/Cadiz","/wiki/Tribune","/wiki/Syria_(Roman_province)","/wiki/Roman_agriculture","/wiki/Cato_the_Elder","/wiki/Marcus_Terentius_Varro","/wiki/Aulus_Cornelius_Celsus","/wiki/Carthage","/wiki/Mago_(agricultural_writer)","/wiki/Tremellius_Scrofa","/wiki/Ancient_Greece","#cite_note-enc-1","/wiki/Italia_(Roman_province)","/wiki/Ardea_(RM)","/wiki/Carsoli","/wiki/Alba_Longa","#cite_note-lacus-2","/wiki/Poggio_Bracciolini","/w/index.php?title=Bartolomeo_di_Mo